Problem_364.question:
Suppose the random variable $X$ has an exponential distribution with mean $1$. Find $\min_{x \in \mathbb{R}} \mathbb{E}|X-x|$. 
\end{problem}
\noindent

Problem_364.reasoning:
Note $\min_{x \in \mathbb{R}} \mathbb{E}|X-x| = \mathbb{E}|X-\pi_{0.5}|$, where $\pi_{0.5} = \ln 2$ is the median of the exponential distribution. 
 $$\mathbb{E}|X-\ln 2| = \int_0^{\ln2} (\ln 2 - x)e^{-x} dx + \int_{\ln 2}^\infty (x - \ln 2)e^{-x} dx = 1+\ln 2.$$

